<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910418-0018</DOCNO><DOCID>910418-0018.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- McDonnell Douglas Corp.:   Up to 350 Jobs to Be Cut   At Helicopter Unit Facilities</HL><DATE>04/18/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6</SO><CO>   MD</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><RE>ARIZONA (AZ)CALIFORNIA (CA)MISSOURI (MO)</RE><LP>   McDonnell Douglas Corp.'s helicopter unit, reeling fromits loss earlier this month in the bid to build the Army'snext-generation attack helicopter, said it will cut up to 350jobs at facilities in Arizona and California, or about 5.9%of its total work force.   McDonnell Douglas Helicopter Co., based in Mesa, Ariz.,currently employs about 5,900 workers.</LP><TEXT>   The unit also plans additional reorganization of itsmanagement. &quot;Among factors influencing the company's decisionare declines in defense spending, loss of the LH {helicopter}contract and increasing competition in the commercialsector,&quot; the unit said. A team led by St. Louis-basedMcDonnell Douglas and Textron Inc.'s Bell helicopter unitlost the LH competition to a team of Boeing Co. and UnitedTechnologies Corp.</TEXT></DOC>